Missing WHERE clause (full scan)
Locking / blocking (other queries holding tables)
Query errors (ambiguous columns, missing GROUP BY)
String operations (LIKE '%...%' — the classic non-sargable pattern)
Sorting on non-indexed columns (ORDER BY date/string vs int)
Missing indexes
Bad joins (cross joins, missing ON, too many joins)

These are literally the 7 most common categories any SQL performance tool needs to detect. You scoped the MVP for me without realizing it.


The big-picture plan (just so you see where we're going):

Week 1 — Collect real queries, build a basic Python parser that detects simple patterns (SELECT *, missing WHERE clauses, obvious index issues)
Week 2 — Read execution plans (XML format) and extract structured info
Week 3 — Build the "explainer" — translate technical problems into human language
Week 4 — Simple CLI, Dockerfile, README, clean GitHub repo → this is already a portfolio-grade MVP

Bonus observation — the "ambiguous column" example:
That's actually not a performance issue, it's a correctness issue (query fails). This is interesting — it tells me the tool could have two modes:

"Why is this slow?" (performance)
"Why is this failing?" (correctness / errors)

We'll come back to that. For now, performance is the focus.


